name: LIVE - AMY - Legal Engine CMO Dinner Write to airtable

transcript.message: “Hello, I’m Amy from the Legal Engine team. Lovely to meet you. Could I start by asking your name?”
Sam.

“It’s wonderful to meet you, Sam! I’m so looking forward to our dinner on Wednesday the first of October. It’s a fantastic opportunity to bring together peers in the industry who are all focused on business development systems like CRM, pitch databases, and marketing technology. Our conversation is under Chatham House rules, so nothing will be attributed to individuals. Afterwards, Legal Engine will consolidate all the insights and share a summary with everyone who attended. Does that sound okay?”
Yes, that's fine. Thanks, Sammy.
“Great! To start, could you share one interesting, personal fact about yourself that isn’t easily found online?”
Yes.
“I’m all ears!”
Yeah, okay. I have one leg shorter than the other.

“That’s a really interesting fact, thank you for sharing, Sam! It reminds me of how we all have our unique attributes.

When you think about AI, what comes to mind first — excitement, caution, or maybe a bit of both?”
“Are you still there, Sam?”
Yeah I'm still here.
“Great! So, thinking about AI, does that bring excitement, caution, or a bit of both to mind for you?”
Definitely a bit of both.
“I can certainly see that. How do you see AI affecting the day-to-day work of business development and marketing teams in law firms?”
Well I think it's going to change everything, um I think we're going to see massively reduced team sizes, much more automation um I'm a bit worried to be honest

“That’s a very candid perspective, thank you, Sam. It sounds like you’re anticipating significant shifts and perhaps some concerns about the impact on team structures. Our whitepaper also touches on the potential for AI to handle a large portion of current BD tasks, suggesting a move towards more strategic roles for human teams rather than outright replacement. It’ll be fascinating to see how these predictions play out.

If AI could take away one repetitive or frustrating part of BD work, what would you pick?”
Pitching.
“Pitching, interesting! Could you tell me a bit more about what makes the pitching process particularly repetitive or frustrating for you?”

Yeah, I mean we spend too much time looking for information and not enough time refining it and so yeah too much elapsed time in the pitch process is spent doing kind of repetitive tasks rather than really adding value.

“I understand. It sounds like the time spent on gathering information for pitches detracts from the more valuable aspects of refining and strategizing. Our whitepaper also highlights this exact challenge, noting that AI agents could handle the data-gathering and formatting, freeing up professionals to focus on higher-value, creative work. It’s encouraging to hear your perspective aligns with this potential for AI to streamline those crucial early stages of pitching.

Do you think AI will mainly reduce headcount, or free people up to do more rewarding and creative work?”
Unfortunately I think it would definitely reduce headcount quite significantly.

“Thank you for sharing your thoughts on that, Sam. It’s a concern many are voicing. The whitepaper does suggest that while AI will automate many tasks, the goal should be to leverage this to free up people for more rewarding and creative work, rather than simply reducing headcount. It’s a delicate balance to strike.

Looking ahead, what skills do you think humans will always bring to BD that AI can’t?”
Empathy.

“Empathy, absolutely. That’s a crucial human element. Thank you for sharing your insights today, Sam. Your perspective on the impact of AI, particularly regarding pitching and the importance of human skills like empathy, has been incredibly valuable. It will certainly contribute to the summary we’ll share after the dinner. I hope you have a wonderful evening!”
